sclosures such as policing statistics for the next 10 years if the municipality wants to raise capital.<p>This beats activist&#x27;s state-level FOIA requests.<p>It doesn&#x27;t harm the ability of an officer to make split second decisions and get home safely, which is usually their argument against any proposal.<p>It doesn&#x27;t require a whole civil suit or criminal suit for anything to happen.<p>Just gets the message across that actions have consequences. It lets them run out of excuses so their real thoughts can be made as clear as day. There are sanctions but I think it doesn&#x27;t practically work because the government is responsible for punishing his people.<p>I think we need private police, subject to the same law as anyone else, and third party arbitration in private courts when something happens. yeah but then you make the cops sad cause they can&#x27;t be shitheels anymore. so that&#x27;s out. If this is the case (I&#x27;m not saying it is or isn&#x27;t), then that is more akin to gestapo tactics and should not be even remotely acceptable by anyone in society. More so those on the right who often draw analogies to the Soviet Union. If you are surprised by these tactics, there are hours and hours of video you should watch from peaceful protests that have occurred over the last 6 months. Surprised? No. Trying to not make a left or right comment? Yes. It&#x27;s an oddity of US politics that this is perceived as a left or right issue at all, in that one &#x27;side&#x27; seems to have adopted the stance that police should be allowed do pretty much anything with no repercussions or meaningful oversight. Outside the lunatic far-right, this sort of thing would be condemned from all sides in many developed democracies. &gt; It&#x27;s an oddity of US politics that this is perceived as a left or right issue at all,<p>There are several major issues like that in US politics.<p>Why is climate change a left or right issue?<p>Why is wearing masks a left or right issue